[SPEAKER_00] videos and social media posts.

291
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] With the aim of keeping users happily immersed in their information bubbles.

292
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Our lives are increasingly driven by abstract metrics that AI algorithms try to optimize or maximize.

293
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] Ratings, likes, views and so on.

294
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] While AI can provide us with tailored content, it also risks numbing our hearts.

295
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] We may end up lacking authentic, transformative experiences and relationships with God, the people around us, and with creation as a whole.

296
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] This shift, as Ratzinger warned, risks reducing human experience to an informative or informational state.

297
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I believe Marshall McLuhan's quote is very suitable in this context.

298
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] We shape our tools and our tools shape us.

299
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] And the reason I'm referencing McLuhan is that AI has revived the claims of technological determinism.

300
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] Which asserts that technology develops independently and shapes society in significant ways.

301
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] Here are just some examples of two of the most prominent representatives of technological determinisms.

302
00:10:54,000 --> 00:11:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] Both Christian philosophers, so Jacques Ellul in 1967, he forwarded the concept of autonomous technology.

303
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] A technology that ultimately evolves beyond human control and conquers every aspect of human society.

304
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] So here the question is, are we witnessing AI augmenting itself?

305
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] At the same time, Marshall McLuhan introduced the concept of technology as an extension of man.

306
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] And the concept of amputation that follows that extension.

307
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] So here we could ask the question, as AI performs tasks in our place, is there a risk that our mental faculties will be amputated hindering our personal development?

308
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, along these lines, more recently, scholar Shannon Valor in 2015 introduced a very interesting concept called moral diskilling.

309
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] And this is also relevant for AI because decision making inherently involves exercising ethical judgment.

310
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] And we are starting to over rely on AI for decision making, which can exacerbate moral diskilling.

311
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] Because as we increasingly delegate our decisions to AI, we might lose the essential skills needed for ethical and moral reasoning.

312
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] As we increasingly interact with the world in an AI mediated way, rather than experiencing it directly, this shift also impacts us as a society.

313
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] This transition is accelerating humanity's path toward what Ratzinger called a global technical worldview, where efficiency and utility become the only criteria of truth.

314
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] At the end of this path, Ratzinger points out that we are in a point where the automatic denial of human development takes place.

315
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] Ratzinger warns against the scenario of living in a technocratic cultural perspective, where we will not be able to discern a meaning that is not of our own making.

316
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] In such a world, the truth will come to be seen coinciding with the possible, because technology will become an ideological power that threatens us to confine us within an a priori that holds us back from encountering meaning and truth.

317
00:12:52,000 --> 00:13:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] Another significant anthropological challenge of AI systems is their action of reducing human users to numerical data.

318
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] So we all interact with recommender algorithms on social networks like YouTube, TikTok, you name it.

319
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] The way these algorithms provide the custom tailored content for each individual is to first construct an algorithmic identity for users.

320
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] So users are replaced in the eye of the AI with an imperfect simplified digital representation.

321
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] Consequently, AI interacts with users based on this digital representation, providing the recommendations.

322
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] So essentially, to participate in an AI-enhanced world, so in the digital world of today, individuals are assigned numbers or reduced to them.

323
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] In this machine-readable world, the reduction to numerical representations has its risks,

324
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] because it risks diminishing the richness and profundity of human identity for the sake of utilitarianism and algorithmic efficiency.

325
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, Ratzinger illustrates this risk in a very interesting meditation he wrote in 1973.

326
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] So he anticipated the world of today, five decades earlier, where he spoke of a world in which machines that men constructed impose their own law on him.

327
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Man must be made readable for the computer, and this can only be achieved when he is translated into numbers.

328
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] So in this world, functions are all that exist, and man becomes a number in itself, everything else in him becoming irrelevant.

329
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] Ratzinger opposes to this beast, so this technological beast, who is a number, and it makes men numbers.

330
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] He opposes God, who has a name, and who calls us by our name.

331
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] God is a person, and he seeks the person.

332
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] He has a face, and he seeks our face.

333
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] He has a heart, and he seeks our heart.

334
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] And for God, we are not some function in a world machinery."

335
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] End of quote.

336
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] Today, we are increasingly encountering the question of whether AI will evolve to become godlike.

337
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, this is associated with its evolution to the AGI level that I mentioned earlier.

338
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] And AI enthusiasts believe that this scenario could soon be plausible, propelling humanity into an unparalleled era of flourishing.

339
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, what's interesting is the discourse around this term, godlike AI.

340
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, you can see it had an increase in recent years.

341
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] And what's shocking is that a quarter of the total mentions of godlike AI all over the internet are in the seven months of 2024.

342
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, when debating the risks associated with AGI, the narrative often focuses on the existential threats, claiming that AGI could potentially destroy humanity.

343
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] However, borrowing from Ratzinger's theological discourse, a more immediate risk lies in humanity's attempt to use AI to gain godlike power over creation.

344
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] Ratzinger identifies this concern, warning of a scenario where humanity places its faith in technological advancements.

345
00:15:52,000 --> 00:16:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] He cautioned that such a reliance on technology could sideline God, disrupting individuals' relationships with the world and with their own lives.

346
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] And he illustrates this risk in a commentary on a medieval Jewish fable.

347
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] A fable in which Jeremiah and his son created a living human being by engineering a correct combination of words and letters,

348
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] which is very similar to what some people are trying to do today with AI.

349
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] When this creature came to life, it changed the inscription on his forehead, which read initially, God is the truth, to God is dead.

350
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] And obviously, Jeremiah asked the creature, why had it done that?

351
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] To which it replied, now that you are able to create a man, God is dead.

352
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] My life is the death of God.

353
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] Where man has all the power, God has no longer any power.

354
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, this narrative is easily connected to the discourse surrounding AI.

355
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] Without the correct understanding of AI's evolution and operation, people might unwittingly be in awe of its power, thereby sidelighting God in their lives.

356
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] Our relationship with God is intricately linked to the relationship we form with the world, ourselves and others.

357
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] As AI permeates the social relationships at various levels, Ratzinger's reflection underscores the imperative of slowing down in our AI augmented lives and reflecting on how technology impacts our relationships and sense of self.

358
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, given that we are approaching the end of our presentation, let's draw some conclusions from the theological critique of AI that we've seen so far.

359
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, first and foremost, I think that we should acknowledge that human creativity comes from God.

360
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] This recognition ensures that our creative potential does not lose its true meaning and direction.

361
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] By doing so, the fruit of our creativity, be it AI or any other technology, can be seen as a synergy between God's love and goodness and human work.

362
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] Additionally, even if we live in an informational digital world powered by AI, it is essential that we do not base our lives on the mere acquisition of information or ideas.

363
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] Instead, we should strive for holistic learning that engages us at a deeper level.

364
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] Our digital experiences and interactions with AI should not remain purely informational.

365
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] They must transition into real-life transformative experiences that foster personal development and interpersonal encounters.

366
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Moreover, we need to be aware that the correct understanding of and relation to technology is crucial for our relationship with God and each other.

367
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] At the same time, we should avoid measuring authentic human development exclusively by technological performance.

368
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] Our worth should not be reduced merely to metrics of technological efficiency.

369
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is also important not to give in to the fascination of technology.

370
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] Instead, we should control its use and development through decisions that arise from moral responsibility.

371
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] And lastly, we should not use technology merely to maximize efficiency and utility, but rather its usage should enable us to re-appropriate the true meaning of freedom.

372
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] Which, as Ratzinger eloquently puts it, is essentially a response to the call of being starting with our own personal being.

373
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, one final idea, if I may.

374
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think that we should, as Christians, be very realistic about the future so we can face it without fear and anxiety.

375
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] We should expect that AI systems will become increasingly more accurate and powerful.

376
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] They might even reach and surpass human-like capabilities in all tasks.

377
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] A form of superintelligence might even be possible one day.

378
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] And some might even call it God-like.

379
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] However, it is essential to recognize a critical distinction.

380
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] And here is where I think Christianity must have a contribution to the technological development.

381
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] And this distinction is that regardless of how well an AI algorithm may perform a task, even if it can do it better than a human,

382
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] it will always remain a mathematical algorithm with the end goal to maximize or minimize a function or a metric.

383
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] Regardless of how human-like an AI interaction feels, or we might have humanoid robots walking around looking and acting just like us.

384
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] For these technologies, we will never be anything more than numerical data.

385
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] Christianity offers a contrasting viewpoint on what it means to be human and how to build a community.

386
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] It teaches that the human person has a name that allows him or her to be addressed.

387
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] The name denotes community.

388
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] As Ratzinger argues, Christianity is not an intellectual system, but an encounter, a love story, and the Christian message is not merely a communication of information, but an experience that makes things happen and is life-changing.

389
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] This profound connection based on love is something no AI can replicate.

390
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] It underscores the unique value of human life and our irreplaceable role in the divine plan.

391
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] As we advance technologically, Christian spirituality of both Eastern and Western traditions should always remind us to cherish this essential aspect of our humanity.

392
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you.

393
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:38,000
[UNKNOWN] Thank you.

